The paper deals with the generation of secret keys in wireless communication systems, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several computer science sub-disciplines. However, the focus of the paper is on the information theory aspects of the problem, such as the impact of full-duplex communication on the secret-key rate and the role of the eavesdropper. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the security implications of the proposed scheme, which suggests that it could be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). Additionally, the paper considers the impact of full-duplex communication on the overall system performance, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.MM (Multimedia).
